  "text": "## Signal Handling for Graceful Shutdown Across Three Major Go Services\n\n### Kubernetes (kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\n**Signal Registration:**\nThe primary signal handler is implemented in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/signal.go`. The `SetupSignalContext()` function registers SIGTERM and SIGINT signals using `signal.Notify(shutdownHandler, shutdownSignals...)`. Platform-specific signal definitions are in:\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/signal_posix.go`: defines `shutdownSignals = []os.Signal{os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM}`\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/signal_windows.go`: defines `shutdownSignals = []os.Signal{os.Interrupt}`\n\nThe signal handler creates a buffered channel with capacity 2, allowing it to handle a first signal for graceful shutdown and a second signal for immediate exit (lines 43-51 of signal.go).\n\n**Shutdown Timeout:**\nThe graceful shutdown timeout is configured in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/genericapiserver.go`. The `RunWithContext()` method implements a multi-stage shutdown:\n- Default shutdown timeout: 60 seconds (configurable via `ShutdownTimeout` parameter, line 585)\n- When `ShutdownSendRetryAfter` is enabled, the HTTP server shutdown timeout is reduced to 2 seconds to allow proper GOAWAY frame handling (lines 586-595)\n- The shutdown delay duration (default 70 seconds) allows graceful termination before closing listeners\n\n**Cleanup Ordering:**\nThe cleanup sequence is documented in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/lifecycle_signals.go` (lines 36-87). The lifecycle follows:\n1. T0: ShutdownInitiated - signal received, /readyz returns red\n2. T0+70s: AfterShutdownDelayDuration - delay passes, pre-shutdown hooks run\n3. T0+70s: HTTPServerStoppedListening - server stops accepting connections\n4. T0+70s to T0+130s: InFlightRequestsDrained - existing requests drain with timeout\n5. Audit backend shutdown occurs only after in-flight requests have drained\n6. The request draining phase waits for non-long-running requests to complete before HTTP server shutdown\n\n### Prometheus (prometheus/prometheus)\n\n**Signal Registration:**\nThe signal handler is implemented in `cmd/prometheus/main.go` (lines 1158-1159) using a run.Group pattern. It registers SIGTERM and SIGINT:\n```go\nterm := make(chan os.Signal, 1)\nsignal.Notify(term, os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM)\n```\n\nAdditionally, SIGHUP is registered separately (lines 1269-1270) for configuration reloads without shutdown.\n\n**Shutdown Timeout:**\nPrometheus implements shutdown timeouts in multiple components:\n- Tracing provider shutdown uses a 5-second timeout in `tracing/tracing.go` (lines 165-168): `context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 5*time.Second)`\n- Notifier queue draining supports conditional flushing via `DrainOnShutdown` option in `notifier/sendloop.go`\n\n**Cleanup Ordering:**\nThe shutdown sequence uses run.Group (oklog/pkg/group) actor-like pattern with ordered component shutdown:\n1. Signal handler stops (lines 1174-1177) - sets web ready state to Stopping\n2. Discovery managers stop (lines 1190-1194, 1204-1207)\n3. Rule manager stops (lines 1219-1222) - before scrape manager to avoid false alerts\n4. Scrape manager stops (lines 1239-1246) - before closing storage to prevent write errors\n5. Tracing manager stops with timeout (lines 1259-1261)\nThe run.Group implementation ensures dependent services stop in correct order before process exit.\n\n### Grafana (grafana/grafana)\n\n**Signal Registration:**\nThe main signal handler is in `pkg/cmd/grafana-server/commands/cli.go` (lines 150-169). It registers both SIGHUP and SIGTERM/SIGINT:\n```go\nsignal.Notify(sighupChan, syscall.SIGHUP)\nsignal.Notify(signalChan, os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM)\n```\n\nAdditional signal handlers are implemented in various operators like `pkg/operators/provisioning/connection_operator.go` (lines 36-42).\n\n**Shutdown Timeout:**\nGrafana implements graceful shutdown with configurable timeouts:\n- Main server shutdown: 30-second timeout in `pkg/cmd/grafana-server/commands/cli.go` (line 162): `context.WithTimeout(ctx, 30*time.Second)`\n- gRPC server shutdown: configurable timeout via `GracefulShutdownTimeout` in `pkg/services/grpcserver/service.go` (lines 184-198)\n- Background services use context-based cancellation in `pkg/server/server.go` and `pkg/server/module_server.go`\n\n**Cleanup Ordering:**\nThe shutdown follows this sequence:\n1. Signal received, context with timeout created (line 162)\n2. Server.Shutdown() called with context (line 164) - calls `managerAdapter.Shutdown()`\n3. Background services drain in reverse order of startup\n4. gRPC server uses select pattern: waits for graceful stop or timeout (lines 192-197)\n5. If timeout occurs, forces stop immediately (line 197)\n6. All service goroutines stop before process exit\n\n### Common Patterns\n\n**Signal Handling Pattern:**\nAll three services:\n- Use buffered signal channels (capacity 1-2) via `signal.Notify()`\n- Register both SIGTERM and SIGINT (Interrupt)\n- Handle graceful shutdown in separate goroutines\n- Support immediate exit on second signal (in Kubernetes) or timeout-based forceful shutdown (in Grafana/Prometheus)\n\n**Timeout Implementation:**\nAll implementations use `context.WithTimeout()` or `context.WithCancel()` for shutdown coordination:\n- Kubernetes: 60-second request drain timeout + 70-second initial delay\n- Prometheus: 5-second component shutdown timeout\n- Grafana: 30-second main shutdown + component-specific timeouts\n\n**Connection Draining:**\nDraining strategies vary:\n- Kubernetes: Drains non-long-running in-flight requests within timeout, then closes HTTP server\n- Prometheus: Uses actor-group pattern for ordered component shutdown, notifier supports optional queue drain\n- Grafana: Background service manager handles cascading shutdown, gRPC server uses timeout-based graceful stop"
